    <name>
      <text>Applying the product law of indices</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>During a digital photography session, a camera stores images in groups. One group contains \({@base@}^{@exp1@}\) image patterns and another contains \({@base@}^{@exp2@}\) patterns.</p>

<p>Write the total number of patterns in index form.</p>

<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>We use the product law of indices:</p>

<p>\[
a^m \times a^n = a^{m+n}.
\]</p>

<p>Here, the base \({@base@}\) is the same in both terms.</p>

<p>So,</p>

<p>\[
{@base@}^{@exp1@} \times {@base@}^{@exp2@} 
= {@base@}^{@exp1 + exp2@}.
\]</p>

<p>Thus the simplified expression is:
\[
{@base@}^{@exp_total@}.
\]</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
